newsitem.title: AUSTRALIA: INSIGHT-Australian 10-yr bond holds familiar range.
newsitem.headline: INSIGHT-Australian 10-yr bond holds familiar range.

text.p: *The Australian 10-year bond futures contract held a familiar trading range during after-hours trading with an eye still on last week's peak after holding support at 92.930.
*Policy easing hopes and a more stable U.S. Treasury market helps to underpin market, but again no local data to trade off.
The September Australian 10-year bond futures contract held a familiar trading range during after-hours trading with an eye still on last week's peak after holding support at 92.930.
The contract ended SYCOM at 92.945 compared with Tuesday's 92.940 pit close after testing the 92.930 level again, but it failed to make progress above a session high of 92.960.

Analysts believe the recent consolidative period will eventually lead to an attack on last week's 3-1/4 year peak of 93.090 set by the expired June contract and once initial firm resistance at 93.015 is taken out.

Monetary policy easing hopes after next week's Reserve Bank board meeting and a more stable U.S. Treasury market helped to underpin the local market, but turnover is likely to suffer again with no key domestic data to trade off.
However, today's release of the quarterly Japanese Tankan survey at 2350 GMT may provide some direction.

U.S. Treasuries showed modest price gains after a reasonably well received two-year note auction on Tuesday, overcoming a weaker tone that followed a rise to a 28-year high in the June Conference Board consumer confidence index. The index rose to 129.6 from a revised 127.9 in May.
